<DESCRIPT>  OBITUARY; NEWSPAPER; ARTS; HUMOR  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Art Sansom, creator of the comic strip "The Born Loser," has died after a long
illness, his editor said. Mr. Sansom was 70.;    He died Thursday at the
Cleveland Clinic, said Sarah Gillespie of the Newspaper Enterprise Association
in New York. He had suffered from a liver ailment, she said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ART SANSOM, 'BORN LOSER' CARTOONIST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "The Born Loser," begun in 1965, is syndicated by NEA to more than 1,200
newspapers worldwide.;    It focuses on the tribulations of potbellied office
worker Brutus Thornapple, whose wife and boss always seem to get the upper
hand.;    NEA said the comic strip would be continued by Mr. Sansom's son and
longtime collaborator, Chip, 39.;    The father-son team won the Best Humor
Strip Award from the National Cartoonist Society in 1988 and 1991.;    Mr.
Sansom began his career at NEA in 1945 after graduating from Ohio Wesleyan
University with a degree in art.;    In addition to his son, Mr. Sansom is
survived by his second wife, Angelyn. His first wife died in 1984.;    A
memorial service is scheduled for Monday in suburban Lakewood.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE>
